  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Dragon's Lair
  author: Kim Seo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    From my father's lips in youth I heard tales of the examination hall spring,
    Where you and the venerable monk shared the same chamber then.
    The dragon coiled in mountain sleeps as dharma thunder rolls and rings,
    The crane soars through heaven's height where poetry's moon shines clear and new.

    Gatama's remnant years of the Way need but staff and simple shoe,
    The society's lofty bonds, once forged, encompass all the nobles' circle.
    In Langzhou, fortune smiles—we have the kinship of old friends,
    At the tea table, I beg you, do not refuse this humble guest.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gatama (迦末) refers to Buddhist renunciation and the simple life of a monk or ascetic
  - key: ''
    value: Langzhou (朗州) was a historical Chinese place name, likely used here metaphorically to represent the poet's locality
  - key: ''
    value: The dragon and crane are traditional symbols of wisdom and transcendence in East Asian poetry
